{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659691"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20886"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20886"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97389"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13761"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80004"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10738"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"12711"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33157"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97389"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAneuploidy is a common chromosomal abnormality that results in an abnormal number of chromosomes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of aneuploidy formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duplication of one chromosome arm with loss of the other","Formation of a circular chromosome structure","Failure of chromosome separation during cell division","Breakage and loss of chromosomal material","Exchange of segments between non-homologous chromosomes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of aneuploidy is \u003Cstrong\u003Efailure of chromosome separation during cell division\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically through nondisjunction. During meiosis or mitosis, chromosomes normally separate to ensure each daughter cell receives the correct number. When this process fails, the resulting cells have too many or too few chromosomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other mechanisms describe different chromosomal abnormalities:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuplication of one chromosome arm with loss of the other\u003C/strong\u003E describes an isochromosome formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of a circular chromosome structure\u003C/strong\u003E describes a ring chromosome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreakage and loss of chromosomal material\u003C/strong\u003E describes a chromosomal deletion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExchange of segments between non-homologous chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E describes a translocation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost autosomal aneuploidies are lethal in embryonic development. Notable exceptions include trisomy 21 (Down syndrome). Sex chromosome aneuploidies like Turner syndrome (45,X) and Klinefelter syndrome (47,XXY) are generally more compatible with life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aneuploidy occurs when cells have an abnormal number of chromosomes, typically resulting from errors in chromosome separation during cell division.","Nondisjunction during meiosis or mitosis is the primary mechanism leading to aneuploidy, resulting in cells with extra or missing chromosomes.","Common viable aneuploidies include trisomy 21 (Down syndrome), monosomy X (Turner syndrome), and XXY (Klinefelter syndrome)."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 165-166"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80004"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20886"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80004"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:42:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:42:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13761"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97389"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10738"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Chromosomal disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12711"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Structural abnormalities of chromosomes","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-04-02T17:06:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02